I have no idea about the US, but in Poland for many decades a traditional dinner always consisted of two courses. The first course traditionally always was a soup, and the second - meat (or much more rarely, someting meat-free) with side dishes, like a salad and potatos. When I was growing up, soup (zupa) and first course (pierwsze danie) were practically synonyms. Things have changed slightly these days, but many families still cultivate the first course+second course tradition.

Looking at the comments, the connection between a soup and a course is more tentative for Americans. Interesting cultural difference, this.

